										<h1>California Road Trip</h1>
									</header>

									<h4><span class="image left"><%= image_tag "california/us.jpg" %></span>San Jose • San Francisco • Mendocino • Redwoods • Modoc • Sequoia • Los Angeles • Joshua Tree • Antelope Canyon • Grand Canyon • Orange County • San Diego • Big Sur</h4>

<p>All of senior year, the future was always in the back of my mind. I need to get a job. I need money. I want to be independent. I don’t want to live at home. I want to do something I love. It was (and still is) a little overwhelming to be honest. My boyfriend and I were in the midst of making big life plans, but one that kept coming back up in conversation was to do something FUN. We were graduating from college and felt the need to go on an exciting trip. After all, this was the first time we would not have the prospect of another semester or year of school looming at the end of our vacation. This was it; we would actually be free. Until we started working of course, and got life figured out. This was how we decided to go on a big road trip. It seemed like the perfect moment, right on the brink of a new stage of life. The west is filled with amazing nature just waiting to be experienced, and we couldn’t wait to explore. With some last minute planning, and pooling both our savings, we were able to plan this post-graduation, pre-real world vacation.</p>

<p>Though I’ve done a fair bit of traveling before (international as well), a lot of it was with either family or a large group. This trip was just the two of us, which made it really exciting and a great learning experience.</p>

<p>We traveled to 13 different places. We took 37 days and drove 4,000 miles.</p>

<p>Excluding a few nights on a friends couch, a few nights at a hostel, and a week at family friends, we camped. It was definitely a lot, but it was also quite the learning experience. Camping may not be many people’s idea of a vacation, but for me, it was a relaxing and fun break from the stressful world. I grew up with frequent family camping trips, but I had not gone in a long time or on my own before (excluding two short beach trips, which honestly didn’t really count). This was quite the test. We were thankfully, and unintentionally, eased into the camp life by beginning at one of the nicest sites, and ending with some of the most rustic. We started in cool northern California. We started off with showers and toilets the first few nights, and by the end of the trip had reached southern Californian heat and vault toilets. It gave us time to ease into the new way of living.</p>

<div class="box alt">
	<div class="row 50% uniform">
		<div class="6u"><span class="image fit"><%= image_tag "california/trolley.jpg" %></span></div>
		<div class="6u"><span class="image fit"><%= image_tag "california/goldenstate.jpg" %></span></div>
